Part I - (Analysis of the Prosper Loan Dataset)¶

by (Joy C. Mokalo)¶

Introduction¶

This data set gives information on 113,937 loans given by Prosper with 81 variables on each loan, including loan amount, borrower rate (or interest rate), current loan status, borrower income, and many others from 2005 to 2014. The data set provides details on general borrower information and performances of the loans.

Reviewing and exploring data set with code to make required changes before analysis and visualization

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset and what features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

The main feature of interest in the data set is the Loan Amount and the following will help the investigation of this feature:¶

      Term of the loan

      Current Status of the loan

      Ratings and Scores

      Location

      Occupation

      Employment status

      Income Range

      Recommendations
    </ol> The aim of this analysis is to confirm if any of the above factors have an influence on the loan amount

# Visualization 5: Distribution to show loan status

plt.figure(figsize = [15, 10]) 

n_loans=df_loan['LoanStatus'].value_counts().sum()
status_count=df_loan['LoanStatus'].value_counts()
status_order=status_count.index

base_color = sb.color_palette()[1]

plt.title('Distribution of Loan Status', fontsize=20)

plt.ylabel('Distribution', fontsize = 15)

plt.xticks(fontsize=12)

locs, labels = plt.xticks(rotation=45) 
# loop through each pair of locations and labels
for loc, label in zip(locs, labels):
    # get the text property for the label to get the correct count
    count = status_count[label.get_text()]
    pct_string = '{:0.1f}%'.format(100*count/n_loans)

    # print the annotation just below the top of the bar
    plt.text(loc, count+2, pct_string, ha = 'center', color = 'black')

Observation 5: Loan performance is not bad, about 49.7% of the loans are current while 33.4% of the loans have been completed. Default loans account for about 4.4% of the data set, while about 10.5% of the loans have been written off¶

Summary¶

    - The loan original amount, which was the variable of interest had a large range of values, so a log transform was used to view data for insights, this showed that \$4,000 was the highest loan amount granted. Other prominent amounts are \\$10, 000, \\$15,000
    - Most of the loans granted didn't have any recommendations
    - Prosper Score '4' and Prosper Rating (Alpha) 'C' were given to most loans disbursed from 2009 t0 2014
    - 2013 had the highest disbursement of loans
    - Middle income earners (i.e \$25k -\$49.9k and \$50k -\$74.9k) took more loans
    - Almost 50\% of the loans are currently running
    - California had the highest number of borrowers
    - The wrangling process was performed on certain variables to make them tidy for analysis and visualization

From the above explorations, the following were deduced:

      - Loan amounts taken fall between \\$1,000 and \\$20,000 and most of the monthly payments were between \\$250 to \\$1,000
      - Employment Status played a role in getting loan grants as majority of loans granted were for individuals with some kind of employment and their home ownerships also influenced the loans granted to them
      - California, Florida, New York, Texas were locations where more loans were disbursed
      - Over 80\% of the loans were either currently running or completed
      - 2013 had the highest disbursement of loans
      - Middle income earners (i.e \$25k -\$49.9k and \$50k -\$74.9k) took more loans and higher loan amounts were usually accompanied by higher monthly repayments

    In addition to the above, the following wrangling efforts were carried out on the following features in the data set:

      - Term of the loan:This was renamed into short, medium and long term. The data type was also converted to category
      - Current Status of the loan: The past due dates were converted into a general category tagged 'past due'. The data type of the column was also changed to category
      - Ratings and Scores: The nulls were filled and the data type was converted to category and int respectively
      - Location: The nulls were filled and the data type was converted to category. Abbreviated states were also changed to the full names of these locations
      - Occupation: The nulls were filled and the data type was converted to category
      - Employment status: The nulls were filled and the data type was converted to category
      - Income Range: The data type was converted to category
